  "body": "I'm writing a few components as ES2015 classes, and I'm trying to understand which methods I should bind in the constructor.\n\nSay I have something like the following code.\n\n``` js\nimport { Component } from 'react'\n\nexport default class ComponentName extends Component {\n  constructor() {\n    super();\n    this.handleClick = this.handleClick.bind(this);\n  }\n\n  handleClick(e) {\n    ...\n  }\n\n  render() {\n    return <div onClick={this.handleClick} />;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nI understand that I must explicitly bind `handleClick` in the constructor (short of using some ES7 stage 0 features). But from this and other examples I've seen, it looks like the `render` method is bound by default &mdash; that is, I don't need to do something like\n\n``` js\nthis.render = this.render.bind(this);\n```\n\nin the constructor. Am I right? How about lifecycle methods like `componentDidMount`? The v0.13 documentation is unclear about this.\n\nAlso, is there anything planned for v0.14 that would change this behavior?\n",
